<subSubSection id="C1826517072EFF81FF93F3C2633D4451" pageId="2" pageNumber="236" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8927369C072EFF81FF93F3C26AA04A7E" blockId="2.[95,1298,3131,3205]" pageId="2" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis id="BBECEA8E072EFF81FF93F3C26BF44A56" bold="true" box="[96,251,3131,3156]" pageId="2" pageNumber="236">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4E984D1F072EFF81FEFDF3C269E74A56" authority="Merriam, 1897" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1897" box="[270,744,3131,3156]" class="Mammalia" family="Geomyidae" genus="Thomomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="2" pageNumber="236" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mazama">Thomomys mazama Merriam, 1897</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="39F03CC1072EFF81FD0FF3C26AA04A7E" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3799834336" pageId="2" pageNumber="236">
“Crater Lake, Mt. 
<taxonomicName id="4E984D1F072EFF81FBF6F3C26F744A56" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1897" box="[1029,1147,3131,3156]" class="Mammalia" family="Geomyidae" genus="Thomomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="2" pageNumber="236" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mazama">Mazama</taxonomicName>
, [Klamath County] Oregon,” USA.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8927369C072EFF81F84EFEE7633D4451" blockId="2.[1981,2574,286,713]" pageId="2" pageNumber="236">
Placed into subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4E984D1F072EFF81F70BFEE76273473D" authorityName="Wied-Neuwied" authorityYear="1839" box="[2296,2428,286,319]" class="Mammalia" family="Geomyidae" genus="Thomomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="2" pageNumber="236" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Thomomys</taxonomicName>
. Formerly regarded: as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4E984D1F072EFF81F696FEBC61094764" authorityName="J. A. Allen" authorityYear="1893" box="[2405,2566,325,358]" class="Mammalia" family="Geomyidae" genus="Thomomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="2" pageNumber="236" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="monticola">1. monticola</taxonomicName>
. Subspecies tacomensis, named by W. P. Taylor in 1919, known only from the vicinity of Tacoma, Pierce County, Washington,is probably extinct as a result of urban expansion. Fourteen extant subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
